// @NAME: Loft Language
// @TITLE: A statically-typed scripting language inspired by Rust.

// Welcome! Loft is a concise, statically-typed language designed to be safe
// and easy to embed in larger projects. These documentation pages are your
// guided tour — each one is also a live test, so every example you see has
// already been verified to work exactly as shown.

// The best way to get started is to read the pages in order. This first page
// introduces the handful of ideas that shape every other part of the language.
// Later pages go deeper on text, numbers, structs, collections, and more.

// ## No type declarations for local variables
// Loft figures out the type of a variable from what you assign to it.
// You never write 'let x: integer = 5' — just write 'x = 5' and move on.
// The compiler still checks types strictly; it just does the bookkeeping for you.

// ## Implicit return
// The last expression in a function body is automatically its return value.
// Short helper functions need no 'return' statement, which keeps them clean.

// ## Null is visible, not hidden
// Any value can be null unless you mark it otherwise. The type system tracks
// this, so you always know which variables might be null and can handle them.
// A null value behaves like false in a condition — easy to test.

// ## Text is UTF-8
// Text in Loft is stored as UTF-8, the same encoding used on the web.
// 'len()' counts bytes, not visible characters. Be mindful of multi-byte
// characters like emoji when slicing text by position.

// ## Collections share their records
// Vectors, sorted trees, and hash maps are not separate silos. They share
// their underlying storage and can be combined inside a single struct, so you
// can index the same data in multiple ways without copying anything.

// ## Hello, Loft!
// Here is a small first program to make things concrete.
// 'println' prints a line of text to standard output.
// Format strings let you embed values directly: write the variable inside '{}'.

fn main() {
    greeting = "Hello, Loft!";
    assert(greeting == "Hello, Loft!", "Variable holds the assigned text");

    x = 6;
    y = 7;
    assert(x * y == 42, "Arithmetic works as you would expect");

    assert("{greeting} The answer is {x * y}." == "Hello, Loft! The answer is 42.", "Format strings interpolate expressions");
}
